		<p>There is no mystery about the look of Comanche.  He is stuffed and mounted in the natural science museum at the University of Kansas, Lawrence, Kansas.  He is in a glass case with saddle and bridle in place.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Melani Van Petten, 3-29-09</b>
		<p>There is no doubt that Comanche was what we would call a buckskin. Black and white photos of the 19th century tended to distort some colors; in photos of cavalry uniforms, for example, yellow trim comes out looking dark. Here is Comanche in color, as he appears today at the University of Kansas: <a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http://www.geocities.com/Yosemite/trails/3539/Comanche.jpg">http://www.geocities.com/Yosemite/trails/3539/Comanche.jpg</a></p>
		
		<b>Comment By Robert Doyle, 4-17-09</b>
		<p>Aside from the inaccuracies detailed by E. Kimber above, most of what Deanne Stillman writes about Myles Keogh is utter rubbish. I am not, per say, blaming the author but the sources for her information on Keogh being a wild drunk have long been discredited. <br />
<br />
The "swaggering bibulous soldier of fortune" nonsense comes from Van De Water in Glory Hunter. He and the dreaded Fred Dustin were hobnobbing (via correspondence at least) when VDW was writing the book, so no doubt it's a piece of gratuitous embroidery on the "information" Dustin got from a cavalry deserter. <br />
<br />
That Keogh drank is not in dispute; almost everyone did in those post-Civil-War days. That he sometimes drank to excess is not disputed either. Mrs. Custer, in her book Following the Guidon, fixed that image of him for all time with her anecdote about the Irish officer who "sometimes became so hopelessly boozy" that he had thought it wisest to turn all his worldly goods over to his striker [his soldier-servant] for safe-keeping. But it was the indefatigable Fred Dustin, purveyor of the "Wild I" myth, who added in the "brute" element, with a story about a drunken Keogh chasing offending troopers and beating them with his cane. His source for this is dubious -- a self-confessed deserter -- and the conclusions that others have drawn from it ("hated") are at variance with much evidence that in fact Keogh was uncommonly well-liked by the men. A C. Rallya, in Winners of the West: "Every man in our troop idolised Captain Keogh". Sergeant John Ryan: "a good-hearted officer". Blacksmith Henry Bailey: "a nice man". Lt. Henry Nowlan (pictured right): "… his brave troopers, who dearly loved him …". An unnamed former 7th Cavalry private: "The names of most of the leading men of the 7th have left me. But a few can still be recalled. There was Captain Gillette of C Troop, a wild reckless officer who had little regard for God, Man or the Devil. Capt. Keho [sic] was just the opposite. He acted as chaplin [sic] and called all the men 'my boys'". Keogh's first biographer, Edward S. Luce, was deeply suspicious of the Dustin story, having had the privilege of asking Mrs. Custer herself about the truth of the matter. She dispelled for Luce any notion that Keogh was "a mean drunk"; she said he was never belligerent "in his cups", but always benign, happy, and inclined towards singing. She went on to describe him as unfailingly gentle by nature. She knew him; Dustin did not; we can draw our own conclusions.<br />
<br />
For facts, visit <a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.myleskeogh.org">http://www.myleskeogh.org</a></p>
		
		<b>Comment By Robert Doyle, 4-17-09</b>
		<p>The charge-across-the-prairie story is from the memoirs of David Burton Long, who was, or claims to have been, a hospital steward at Fort Wallace. Although Long cites the "charge" incident as an example of drunken antics, the incident could have stemmed from an actual threat of attack on the Fort. As early as February 1867, Keogh was telling his brother Tom he expected attacks on the post "soon"; after that, he had months and months with his men spread ever thinner and the Indians ever more troublesome.<br />
<br />
And in any case again, Long gives us nothing to substantiate that this was "an imaginary enemy". He, after all, went back to sleep. For all he knows, there might indeed have been Indians out there. OK, they didn't catch any on this foray, but that doesn't mean a thing; most of their daylight sorties were just as abortive, with Indians melting away when pursued. He doesn't exactly make out a forensically watertight case.<br />
<br />
That he should have this outing begin at midnight is kind of interesting. When Keogh later that year gives Tom his daily timetable, he makes the point that when officer of the day he has to do a round at midnight. It seems most likely that it's on such an occasion that he'd see something that he thought warranted calling "Boots and Saddles". However he might indulge at other times, it seems most unlikely that he'd get roaring drunk when he was officer of the day; if he did, we'd surely have far more "drunk on duty" allegations floating about than this solitary, unsubstantiated, one, if not actual formal charges. Yet there's nothing.<br />
<br />
Finally, and for what it's worth, though I personally think it ought to be worth a lot: if he's such a drunken buffoon, endangering and wearing out his men for nothing -------- why would 7th cavalry troopers like McIlhargey, Mitchell, Kelly, and (if I remember correctly) Lloyd sign up to serve under him for a second term of enlistment? They could easily transfer to someone else. It does not compute.<br />
<br />
Fact Ms. Stillman, facts</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Robert Doyle, 4-17-09</b>
		<p>A finally, finally...while researching for <a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.myleskeogh.org">http://www.myleskeogh.org</a>, we uncovered that existance of another "Miles Kehoe', with a different spelling of his names.<br />
<br />
Captain Miles Kehoe was posted in the Missouri-Arkansas area for most of the war but never promoted and it appears that his military career ended in shame;<br />
<br />
"United States Army. Department of Arkansas. Special Orders, No. 20. Little Rock;<br />
Jan. 21, 1865, Section 6 of Special Order No. 20 concerning Captain Miles Kehoe, Company "A", First Missouri Cavalry Volunteers, and his dishonorable dismissal from the military for drunkenness and disorderly conduct.<br />
By order of Major General J.J. Reynolds."<br />
<br />
Interestingly, Irishman, Myles Keogh, was in the adjoining state of Kentucky at the exact time of Miles Kehoe's dismissal from the military for "drunkenness and disorderly conduct". Any future researcher into 'Keogh of the 7th' may have mistakenly received factual information about a drunken cavalry officer called Miles Kehoe and perceived it to refer to Custer's Irish officer.<br />
<br />
Reda more about this at <a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.myleskeogh.org%2F2009%2F01%2Fcaptain-miles-kehoe-1st-missouri-union.html">http://www.myleskeogh.org/2009/01/captain-miles-kehoe-1st-missouri-union.html</a></p>
		
