		<b>Comment By Betty Kelly, 8-07-11</b>
		<p>8-7-2011 I would like to add Rae Jo Melin’s concerns, particularly Comanche shoved in a corner in a glass case mentality in Kansas.  Over the years, the Nevada State Museum in CC NV has gutted and eliminated the significance of America’s wild horses-burros in our state, except for the survival of a reportedly 10,000 year old ancient wild horse skeleton uncovered from the Winnemucca NV area.  Like Comanche, the skeleton continues to be intentionally hid against a back wall in a poorly lighted room. There is little persuasively history in the most recently renovated museum. In the past, the museum honored these precious wild ones more appropriately with less hidden exhibits and evolutionary information about them.  Now there is no info about WHBs in their store.  If you asked about any such info, the response is a perplexing “What’s a wild horse?”  The museum has been stuffed with propaganda about the prejudicial domestic livestock/mining industries that not only detests America’s wild horses-burros, but are methodically stealing America’s public lands and water as their “private” property.   Special interest politicians, controlled by these industries, are destroying “the (perfect) horse they rode in on”.  <br />
<br />
Anyone who is involved with horses must read Deanne Stillman’s book, MUSTANG, which tells the saga like it is, whether some people agree or not with some details, its history and it’s true about the horse surviving then and now in its ongoing antagonistic cradle of evolution on the North American continent.  The Western free-roaming wild horse-burro is not a feral-non-native species, but is a North American native species by well documented paleontological and Mitochondrial DNA evidence. So be educated!<br />
<br />
Betty Kelly <br />
